[{"id": "626acaae-99c1-4272-902a-04d9cdffc239", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "USER: what do you think of these stats?\n\nTechnically, We're the Same Person (2,308 words)\nSubscriptions: 2 Hits: 2,434 Kudos: 85 Comment Threads: 1 Bookmarks: 21\nASSISTANT: These are solid stats for a ~2.3k word one-shot on AO3. Here's the breakdown:\n\n**Kudos/Hit ratio: ~3.5%** \u2014 This is right around the AO3 average (3-5%), which is decent. Not jaw-dropping, but healthy.\n\n**Bookmarks: 21** \u2014 This is where it gets interesting. Your bookmark-to-kudos ratio is roughly 25%, meaning a quarter of people who left kudos also bookmarked. That's strong. Bookmarks require more effort than kudos and usually signal \"I want to come back to this\" or \"this resonated.\" That's a loyalty indicator.\n\n**Comments: 1** \u2014 Low, but comments are always the hardest metric to get. Most readers are lurkers. Still, if you want more engagement, ending with a question or author's note inviting discussion can help.\n\n**Subscriptions: 2** \u2014 Normal for a completed shorter work. Subs spike with WIPs or series.\n\n**Hits: 2,434** \u2014 Good visibility for the word count. You're getting into the circulation.\n\nThe overall picture: The work found its audience and stuck with a subset of them. The high bookmark ratio relative to kudos suggests it hits harder for people who connect with it than a casual kudos-and-leave fic. The low comments are the weakest point, but that's the norm.\n\nWhat's the fandom and tagging situation? That context would explain a lot about whether these numbers are overperforming or underperforming for the niche.", "embedding": [-0.07017256319522858, -0.11410557478666306, -0.04603312909603119, 0.03653642535209656, -0.0010069288546219468, 0.02586008608341217, 0.08929626643657684, 0.05024115741252899, 0.02571224607527256, 0.023571964353322983, -0.02146061696112156, -0.010368403047323227, 0.09877000004053116, -0.026303881779313087, 0.017359884455800056, 0.08685238659381866, 